# Thesis Notes

When we encounter a finding, insight, or result that would strengthen the bachelor thesis, add it to `THESIS_NOTES.md` in the project root.

## When to Log

- Platform limitations discovered (things Salesforce can't do)
- Architectural decisions and why one approach was chosen over another
- Performance measurements or before/after comparisons
- Security or compliance-relevant findings (data residency, trust boundaries)
- Real-world friction encountered during development (sandbox quirks, API constraints)
- Successful demonstrations that a feature works as intended

## Format

```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD — Short descriptive title

1-3 paragraphs explaining the finding, why it matters, and how it relates to the thesis topic (data privacy in Salesforce sandboxes). Include concrete numbers, API names, or error messages where relevant.
```

## Rules

- New entries go at the bottom of the file (chronological order).
- Write in a factual, report-friendly tone — these notes will feed directly into the thesis.
- Focus on the *why it matters* angle, not just the technical detail.
- If `THESIS_NOTES.md` does not exist yet, create it with a top-level `# Thesis Notes — Strong Points` heading.
- Do not duplicate entries that already exist in the file.
